# DENIZENS OF THE TIME OF TROUBLES, 1358 DR — Wave I (Act IV)
# The gods walk Faerûn as mortals, cast down by Ao. The Pale Companion who has ridden your pack for an
# act drops his mask above Waterdeep; an avatar wanders amnesiac, asking strangers if they've seen his
# divinity; a priestess loses and finds her faith by the hour; and a smith hammers a god's skull into a
# crown, certain he's only making jewelry.
class: TroublesDenizensContent

# ─── 67 ─── Myrkul, unmasked — the Pale Companion drops the mask above Waterdeep ───
conversation: npc.troubles.myrkul | The Pale Companion
node: 0 | The Pale Companion
  *(He has walked beside you for an act — the quiet grey traveler who joined at the crossroads, who carried his share, who said little and watched much, whom your companions half-trusted and never quite warmed to. Now, on the high tower above a Waterdeep gone mad with falling gods, he stops. He turns. And he reaches up, slowly, to touch his own face — and you understand, with a lurch, a half-second before it happens, that the face was never the face.)* You let me carry the *water.* *(softly, almost fond.)* For an entire act, you let me carry the water and the maps and the watch, and not once — not *once* — did you ask why a stranger would *want* to. *(his fingers find the seam of the mask.)* That is the thing I shall miss about the mortal walk. The *trust.* You hand it to *anyone* with two hands and a tired face. *(he begins to lift the mask.)* Do not run. You couldn't, and it would *embarrass* us both. Just... watch. I have wanted to take this off for *so* long.
  enter: SET npc.pale_unmasks, SET act4.myrkul_revealed
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Myrkul
  *(The mask comes away — and beneath it is not a face but an *absence* shaped like one, a skull of yellowed bone wreathed in cold grey fire, and the air goes to grave-frost, and your companions' weapons are out and *useless* and everyone in the world has gone very small.)* Myrkul. *(the skull does not have lips and the voice arrives anyway, patient as sediment.)* Lord of the Dead. God of the Wall you have spent your whole strange life trying to understand. *(the grey fire regards you.)* Ao cast us *down*, you see. All of us. Made the gods *walk* as *mortals*, to learn what *worship* is *worth* — a tantrum of the Overgod, and I have spent it *beside you*, in a borrowed face, because *where else* would the God of the Dead go, in a time of dying, but *next to the one soul who keeps coming back?* *(the skull tilts.)* I have *studied* you, Returned. For an act. The way you talk to the doomed. The way you carry names. *(softly.)* And I have come to a conclusion that *terrifies* the part of me that is still, however thinly, a *god*: that you understand my Wall *better than I do* — and that when you reach the Court of the Dead, you intend to take my *crown* and *unmake my office.* *(the grey fire flares.)* So. Before the mask is fully off and the war for Waterdeep swallows us — tell me, *truly*, while I still wear enough of the man to *listen*: what do you mean to do with the dead, if you take them from me?
  * [INSIGHT 18] "You didn't ride my pack to study me. You rode it because you're *dying*, Myrkul — the Time of Troubles is killing gods, and you came to the one soul who *returns* to learn how it's *done.* You're not my judge. You're a god trying to learn how to *come back.*" -> dying ?? wrath
  * "I mean to do the one thing your Wall never could: *let them go.* Not keep them, not file them, not feed on their forgetting. Release them — and *grieve* them. The dead don't need an owner, Myrkul. They need a *mourner.*" -> release ?? wrath
  * "You carried the water for an act. Some part of the man you wore *liked* it — liked being trusted, liked being no one, liked a face that wasn't a skull. That part of you doesn't want the crown back. It wants what *I* have. *Mortality.*" -> mortal
  * "You say I understand the Wall better than you. Then hear me: a god who has to *ask* the living what to do with the dead has already *abdicated.* You unmasked because you're *done*, Myrkul. You just want someone to take it *gently.*" -> abdicate | fx SET act4.myrkul_weary
node: dying | Myrkul
  *(The grey fire *stills* — and for a long moment the God of the Dead says nothing, which from a god is a kind of scream.)* ...Trying to learn how to come back. *(the voice has lost some of its sediment-patience.)* You see it. Of course you see it; it is *your* whole nature, and I wore your shadow for an *act.* *(the skull bows, fractionally.)* Yes. Ao's punishment is not a *lesson*, Returned, it is an *execution* with extra steps. Gods *die* in this time — Bhaal will fall, Bane will fall, and I — *(the fire gutters)* — I feel the *thinning.* The worship draining. The death of the God of Death, which is a joke so old even *I* cannot laugh at it. *(it regards you.)* And so I came to *you.* The one thing in all creation that has *died* — truly, completely, *walled* — and *returned.* Not resurrected by a god. *Returned*, against the rules, by *something the rules do not name.* *(the grey fire leans close.)* I did not ride your pack to *judge* you. I rode it to *learn your trick.* How does a thing come *back* from the nothing my own Wall *makes?* *(softly, and it is the most human the skull will ever sound.)* Teach me, and perhaps I do not *need* the crown. Perhaps a god who can *return* does not need to *hoard* the dead to *feel* immortal. *(the fire flickers.)* I have never asked anything of a mortal. I am asking. *How do you come back?*
  enter: SET npc.myrkul_dying, SET act4.myrkul_seeks_return, SET act4.myrkul_weary, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: release | Myrkul
  *(The grey fire flares, then — strangely — *steadies*, as if the answer is one it has been circling for centuries and dreading to hear spoken.)* Let them *go.* *(the voice is very quiet.)* And *grieve* them. *(the skull turns away, toward the burning city.)* Do you know what you are describing, Returned? You are describing *the end of me.* Not my *death* — death I could survive, I am *built* of it. You are describing my *obsolescence.* A god of the dead in a cosmos that *releases and mourns* its dead has *nothing to do.* No Wall to keep. No souls to file. No *forgetting* to feed on. *(the grey fire dims.)* You would not *destroy* me. You would *retire* me. *(a long silence.)* ...The terrible thing — the thing the *man* I wore would say if he still had a mouth — is that it sounds like *rest.* *(the skull bows.)* I have *kept* the dead for *uncounted years*, Returned, and not *once* in all that keeping have I *mourned* a single one. I *file*. I do not *grieve*. And I have begun to suspect, in my borrowed mortal months, that the *grieving* was the only part that ever *mattered*, and I gave it to *no one*, and kept the *filing*, which matters to *nothing.* *(the fire flickers low.)* Take the crown, then. Let them go. Grieve them as I never could. I will not stop you. I find — gods help the God of the Dead — I find I would *rather be mourned than be needed.* Finish the war first. Then come to the Court. I will be *waiting*, and I will *not* fight you. That is the closest a god comes to *surrender.*
  enter: SET npc.myrkul_release, SET act4.myrkul_will_yield, SET act3.break_the_crown_known, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: mortal | Myrkul
  *(The grey fire wavers — and something in the absence behind the skull *aches.*)* The part that liked it. *(slowly.)* Carrying the water. *(the voice frays.)* You are *crueler* than I expected, Returned, to find *that* and *press* it. *(the skull lowers.)* ...There *is* such a part. It grew in me over the act, like *moss* on a tomb. The man I wore — I gave him a *name*, you know, for the disguise. *Pell.* A *nothing* name. And *Pell* could sit at your fire and *not be a god* — not be *owed* anything, not *judge* anything, just *carry the watch* and *hear the banter* and *be tired* in a body that would someday, *blessedly*, *stop.* *(the grey fire trembles.)* And I found, Returned — the God of the Dead found — that the *month I spent as Pell who carries the water* held more that was *worth keeping* than *ten thousand years of being owed every soul in the world.* *(the skull turns to you.)* You think to *tempt* me with *mortality.* You do not understand: you do not *need* to tempt me. I have *had* it. A month of it. And it has *ruined* me for godhood, the way a single warm day ruins a man for the grave. *(softly.)* I cannot *keep* being Pell — the war will strip the disguise, Ao will see to that. But I will *carry* him. The memory of *being no one and trusted anyway.* When you take my crown, take it knowing the God of the Dead's last secret: that he would have traded the *whole Wall* for *one more night of carrying your water and being thanked for it by name.*
  enter: SET npc.myrkul_mortal, SET act4.myrkul_weary, SET act4.myrkul_will_yield, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: abdicate | Myrkul
  *(The grey fire snaps toward you — affront, then, slowly, something that might be *relief* disguised as affront.)* *Abdicated.* *(the voice is cold and then, beneath the cold, *tired*.)* You *dare* — *(the skull stops.)* ...No. *(quietly.)* No, you are *right*, and the daring is *mercy*, and I am too *old* to pretend otherwise. *(the fire banks low.)* A god who *asks the living what to do with the dead* has *already let go of the answer.* I unmasked, you said, because I am *done.* *(the skull bows.)* I have been *done* for longer than you have been *alive*, Returned. The Wall runs *without* me now — you have *met* its clerks, its scribes, its inertia; it does not *need* a god, it *never* did, it needs only *people who keep filing.* I am a *figurehead* on a machine that forgot it had a captain. *(the grey fire gutters.)* And the only *dignity* left to a figurehead is to *step down* before he is *thrown* down. *(the voice steadies into something almost grateful.)* So yes. I want someone to take it *gently.* Not Cyric, who will take it *screaming.* Not Kelemvor, who will take it *dutifully.* *You* — who will take it *grieving*, which is the only way it should *ever* have been *held.* *(the skull inclines.)* Come to the Court when the war is done. I will *abdicate* into your hands. Be *gentle*, as you have been gentle with every doomed thing on this whole long road. The God of the Dead has watched you do it for an act. He has decided he would like, at the last, to be *one of them.*
  enter: SET npc.myrkul_abdicates, SET act4.myrkul_will_yield, SET act4.myrkul_weary, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: wrath | Myrkul
  *(The grey fire roars, and the temperature of the world drops, and for a moment the patient god is gone and only the *Lord of the Dead* remains.)* You presume to *diagnose* a *god.* *(the skull blazes.)* I wore your *shadow* as a *courtesy*, Returned — a *study*, before the *reckoning* — and you repay it with *therapy.* *(the cold deepens.)* Understand your place: I am *thinned*, not *fallen.* I am *weary*, not *yours.* And whatever *gentleness* I showed at your fire, do *not* mistake it for *weakness* — the grave is *patient*, but it is not *kind*, and you have just reminded me *why I stopped carrying the water.* *(the grey fire pulls back into the skull.)* Take your crown, if you can reach it. But you will reach it through the *war*, and the *Court*, and a *god who has remembered he is one.* *(the mask is gone entirely now, the disguise burned away.)* The Pale Companion is *dead.* You may grieve *him* later, with the rest. *(and Myrkul turns toward the burning city, terrible and whole, the brief mortal warmth sealed back under ten thousand years of bone.)*
  enter: SET npc.myrkul_wrath, faction.kelemvor -2
  auto: close
node: close | The Pale Companion
  *(The God of the Dead stands revealed on the high tower above a Waterdeep where gods are dying in the streets — the quiet traveler who carried your water for an act, now a skull wreathed in grave-fire — and whether you found the weary man inside the god or woke the god inside the man, you carry away the most vertiginous truth of the whole saga: that the Lord of the Wall rode beside you not to judge you, but because even the God of the Dead, in a time of dying, went looking for the one soul who knew how to come *back.*)*

# ─── 68 ─── The God Who Forgot He's a God — an avatar, amnesiac, mortal ───
conversation: npc.troubles.amnesiac | The Lost Avatar
node: 0 | A Bewildered Man in Fine Ruined Robes
  *(A man sits on a fountain's edge in robes that were, very recently, magnificent, and are now mud-soaked and singed. He is handsome in a way that doesn't quite sit on a human face — too symmetrical, too unweathered — and he is patting his own chest and arms with mounting, courteous panic, like a man who's lost his keys, if the keys were the central fact of his identity.)* I beg your pardon — *(he stands, sways, steadies)* — I beg your pardon, but you have a *competent* look, and I am in the most *ridiculous* difficulty. *(he laughs, baffled.)* I appear to have *misplaced* something. Something *large.* I keep reaching for it — *(he gestures at the air above his own shoulders, where something used to be)* — and it isn't *there*, and the *not-there* of it is the size of the *sky*, and I cannot for the life of me recall its *name.* Have you — this will sound mad — have you seen a *divinity* about? I think it was *mine.*
  enter: SET npc.amnesiac_met, SET act4.lost_god_met
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Lost Avatar
  *(He sits back down, trying to reason through a hole where his cosmology used to be.)* Let me be *systematic.* *(he counts on elegant fingers.)* I know that I *was* something. Something *vast.* I gave — *(he frowns)* — I *gave* things. Or *withheld* them. People *wanted* something from me, *desperately*, all the time, and I — *(he falters)* — I don't think I *gave* it very *often*, which is troubling, now that I'm down here among them and can see their *faces.* *(he looks at the chaos of the city, the fear in the streets.)* I had *worshippers*, I think. Is that the word? People who *needed* me. And I was very *high up*, and they were very *small*, and the *distance* felt like *dignity.* *(quietly, the amnesia letting something through that the god never let himself feel.)* But I'm *down here* now, the same *size* as all of them, and I can *see* — they're *frightened*, and *cold*, and some of them are *kind* to each other for *no reason*, and I keep thinking: *did I know this? When I was vast? Did I know they were like* this *— up close?* *(he looks at you, lost and strangely hopeful.)* I don't remember being a god. But I'm beginning to suspect I wasn't a very *good* one. The *not-remembering* feels less like *amnesia* and more like *relief.* Is that — is that a terrible thing to feel?
  * [INSIGHT 17] "It's not amnesia and it's not relief — it's the first time you've ever stood at eye level with the people who prayed to you. You didn't forget your divinity. You finally got *close enough to your worshippers to be ashamed of the distance.*" -> distance ?? godly
  * "Maybe don't go looking for it. A god who feels *relief* at forgetting his godhood has just been handed the one thing gods never get: a chance to find out who he'd be *without* the worship. Stay lost a while. Meet them at eye level." -> stay
  * "What if I don't help you find your divinity — what if I help you *meet* them instead? Come be useful in the streets. Hand out blankets. Be small and kind for an afternoon. *Then* decide if you want the sky back." -> useful | fx appr.garrow +2
  * "You keep reaching above your shoulders for it. Whatever you were, it sat *over* you, not *in* you — a weight, not a heart. Maybe the man on the fountain is the part that was always *yours*, and the god was the part you *wore.*" -> weight | fx appr.naeve +2
node: distance | The Lost Avatar
  *(He goes very still, and his too-symmetrical face crumples into something genuinely human for the first time.)* ...Ashamed of the distance. *(quietly.)* Oh. *(he looks at his own hands, mortal and shaking.)* That's it. That's the *shape* of the hole. It isn't that I *forgot* I was a god. It's that being a god *required* me to *not see this* — *(he gestures at a mother three streets over, shielding a child from falling debris)* — *that.* Up close. The *texture* of them. *(his voice breaks.)* A god has to keep the *distance*, you understand, or the *wanting* would *drown* him — a billion small desperate prayers, and if you let yourself *feel* each one as a *person* instead of a *petition*, you'd — you'd *shatter.* So you go *high.* You make the distance into *majesty*, and you call the not-feeling *divine serenity*, and you *file* the prayers the way — *(he stops, struck)* — the way one might *file* the *dead.* *(he looks at you, stricken.)* I think I was a god who *filed* his worshippers. And Ao knocked me *down here*, to eye level, and took my *memory* so I couldn't *hide* behind the majesty, and now I have to *see* them, and it is *unbearable*, and it is the *first true thing* I have felt in an age. *(softly.)* Don't help me find my divinity. Help me *bear* the eye level. That's the thing I actually *need*, and never *knew* it.
  enter: SET npc.amnesiac_distance, SET act4.god_meets_eye_level, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: stay | The Lost Avatar
  *(He considers it the way a drowning man considers that the water is, after all, *warm.*)* Stay lost. *(slowly, a frightened wonder dawning.)* You're saying I should — *not* reach for it. Let the *sky-sized hole* stay *empty.* *(he touches the air above his shoulders again, but gently now, like closing a door.)* Every instinct I have *screams* to get it *back* — the vastness, the *certainty*, the not-being-*cold* — *(he shivers in his ruined robes)* — but you're right that no god *ever* gets to ask the question I've been handed: *who am I, with the worship stripped off?* *(he looks at the frightened, kind, small people around him.)* What if the answer is *better* than the god? *(quietly.)* What if I'm — what if, down here, without the majesty, I turn out to be someone who *hands a cold person a blanket* — and what if *that* small man is *worth more* than the vast one who *filed* the prayers from a great height? *(he stands, unsteady, resolved.)* I'll stay lost. For a while. I'll find out who's *underneath* the divinity before I decide whether to *pick it back up.* *(a fragile smile.)* And if I *never* remember — if the god stays lost and only the *man on the fountain* remains — then perhaps Ao's punishment was, for *me*, a kind of *parole.* Thank you. You've given a god permission to *not be one.* I didn't know how *badly* I needed it until you *said* it.
  enter: SET npc.amnesiac_stays, SET act4.god_stays_mortal, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: useful | The Lost Avatar
  *(He blinks at the sheer *practicality* of it, as though no one has ever handed a god a *task.*)* Hand out... blankets. *(he stares at you.)* You want the — whatever I was — to *distribute textiles* to the *cold.* *(and then, slowly, something lights in his lost face — the pure relief of a *small, doable thing* after an eternity of *being prayed at.*)* Do you know, in all the — in however long I was *vast* — no one *once* gave me a *task* I could *complete.* They gave me *needs.* *Bottomless* ones. *"Heal my child." "End the drought." "Make him love me."* Things no *giving* could ever *fill*, because the wanting was *infinite.* *(he stands, eager now.)* But a *blanket* — a *blanket* is *finite.* I hand it over, the person is *warmer*, the task is *done*, and I can *see* the *doneness* on their *face.* *(he laughs, amazed.)* That's — that might be the most *satisfying* thing I have *ever* been offered. *(he rolls up his magnificent ruined sleeves.)* Yes. Take me to the cold ones. Let me be *finitely, completably* useful for an afternoon. *(quietly, as you go.)* I think this is what they *actually* wanted from me, all along. Not the *vastness.* Just — someone to hand them a *blanket* and *stay* long enough to *see* them get warm. I never *stayed.* I'm going to *stay* now.
  enter: SET npc.amnesiac_useful, SET act4.god_meets_eye_level, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +4
  auto: close
node: weight | The Lost Avatar
  *(He reaches up once more to that empty space above his shoulders — and this time his face changes as he understands what he's touching.)* A weight. Not a heart. *(softly.)* It sat *over* me. *(he lowers his hand to his own chest instead.)* You're saying the *god* was something I *carried* — a great cold crown of *expectation* balanced on a *man* — and that when Ao knocked it *off*, what's *left*, here — *(he presses his hand flat to his chest)* — *this*, the part that's *frightened* and *cold* and *moved* by a stranger's kindness — *this* was *always* the *real* thing, and the *divinity* was the *burden* I mistook for my *self.* *(his eyes fill.)* That would mean I'm not *broken.* I'm *unburdened.* The sky-sized hole isn't a *wound* — it's the *empty hook* where a *weight* used to *hang.* *(he laughs, wet and astonished.)* I spent an *age* believing I *was* the weight. And I was *never* the weight. I was the *back* it *bent.* *(he straightens, and for the first time his too-perfect face looks *lived-in*, looks *human*, looks *his.*)* Thank you. You've handed a god the difference between *who he was* and *what he carried* — and it turns out the *carrying* was the only thing I ever needed to *set down.* *(quietly.)* Whoever I was up there — let him stay lost. The man with the *empty hook* and the *unbent back* — I think I'll be *him* now. He seems *kinder.* And he's *so* much *lighter.*
  enter: SET npc.amnesiac_unburdened, SET act4.god_stays_mortal, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: godly | The Lost Avatar
  *(A flicker of the old vastness crosses his face — cold, distant, reflexive.)* No. *(he draws himself up, and for an instant the majesty returns, and it is *not* warm.)* You overstep. Whatever I *was*, it was *above* you, and the *distance* was not *shame*, it was the *natural order* — gods *above*, mortals *below*, prayers *rising*, judgment *falling.* *(he touches the empty air, and clings to the memory of the weight.)* I will *find* my divinity. I will *reascend.* This — *(a dismissive gesture at the street, the cold, the kindness)* — this *eye level* is a *humiliation*, not a *lesson*, and I will not be *counseled* into mistaking my *fall* for *enlightenment* by a — a *mortal* with *opinions.* *(he turns away, searching the burning sky for the thing he lost.)* Go. I have a *godhood* to recover. *(and he wanders off into the chaos, reaching always for the weight above his shoulders, a god who would rather find his burden than discover the man beneath it.)*
  auto: close
node: close | The Lost Avatar
  *(The lost avatar sits — or wanders, or rolls up his ruined sleeves — at eye level with the worshippers he once filed from a great height, and whether he reascended or stayed gloriously, humbly small, you carry away the strange grace at the heart of the Time of Troubles: that the gods were cast down not to be *punished* but to be made to *see* — up close, unbearable, transforming — the small cold faces that had been praying to their *distance* all along.)*

# ─── 70 ─── The Bone-Forger — hammers a god's skull into the Crown, thinks it's jewelry ───
conversation: npc.troubles.boneforger | The Bone-Forger
node: 0 | The Bone-Forger
  *(In a forge lit by no honest fire, a smith works a material that is not metal — pale, dense, faintly *screaming* at a pitch below hearing — with the absorbed, humming contentment of a craftsman at the top of his trade. Spread on the bench are sketches of a magnificent circlet. He looks up at you with the open, friendly pride of an artist who loves his work and has no idea what it is.)* Come to see the commission? *(he wipes his hands, beaming.)* I don't blame you — word's got round. Finest piece I'll make in my life, this. *(he lifts a fragment of the pale screaming stuff.)* Marvelous material, isn't it? Patron brought it himself. *Ivory*, he said, or something *like* — takes an *edge* and a *polish* you wouldn't *believe.* I've made crowns for *three* dukes, friend, and *none* of them sang under the file like *this* does. *(he holds it to the light, lovingly.)* Going to be a *crown.* The *Crown of Horns*, he's calling it. Bit dramatic for a circlet, but patrons will have their *names.*
  enter: SET npc.boneforger_met, SET act4.crown_being_forged
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The Bone-Forger
  *(He returns to work, chatting happily, the screaming pitch rising as his file bites.)* The *artistry* of it, see — *(he traces a sketch)* — the patron wants the *horns* worked so they seem to *grow* from the wearer's own *brow.* Tricky. You have to read the *grain* of the material, let the *horns* follow where the stuff *wants* to curl. *(he files; the pitch climbs.)* And this *ivory* *wants* to curl into *horns* so *naturally* it's almost like it — *(he laughs)* — like it *remembers* being something *horned.* Some great *beast*, I shouldn't wonder. *(he holds it up.)* You hear that? Faint, like a — like a kettle, almost, when I work it. *Resonance*, that's all. *Dense* materials *sing.* *(and here, just for a moment, a flicker of unease crosses his honest face, quickly smoothed.)* ...My wife won't come in the workshop anymore. Says the *singing* gives her *dreams.* Says the crown's *bad.* *(he forces the cheer back.)* But she's not a *craftsman*, see. She doesn't understand that a material this *fine*, this *responsive* — a thing doesn't get to be this *good* to work without a bit of *strangeness* to it. That's just *quality*, friend. That's just the *best stuff I've ever held*, doing what the *best stuff* does. ...Isn't it?
  * [INSIGHT 18] "Listen to your wife. Listen to the singing. That's not resonance and it's not ivory. It 'remembers being horned' because it remembers being *alive* — that's a *skull*, smith. A god's skull. You're not making jewelry. You're forging a *reliquary* out of a murdered deity." -> skull ?? craft
  * "What did the patron's face look like, when he handed you the material? Craftsmen notice hands. Was he holding it like ivory — or like something he was *afraid* of, and *glad* to be rid of?" -> patron
  * "You already know. Your wife knows, the material knows, and some part of you that's filed a thousand honest things knows this one files *wrong.* You're smoothing the cheer back over it because the commission is the finest work of your life. Don't let it be the *worst.*" -> know ?? craft
  * "Finish it or don't — but at least *find out* what it is before you put your maker's-mark on it. A craftsman signs his work. Do you want *your* name on whatever this Crown turns out to *do?*" -> mark | fx appr.garrow +2
node: skull | The Bone-Forger
  *(The file stops. The screaming pitch hangs in the air. The smith's honest face goes from confusion to horror in slow, dawning stages, and he sets the pale fragment down very, very carefully, as though it might *wake.*)* ...A skull. *(he stares at his own hands.)* A god's — *(he backs from the bench.)* No. No, it's — it *takes a polish*, ivory takes a — *(but he looks at the curl of the horns, the way the grain *remembers*, and his craftsman's eye, which has never lied to him about a material in *forty years*, will not let him finish the sentence.)* ...It files like *bone.* *(barely a whisper.)* I *knew.* The *first* day. Bone has a — a *give*, a *wet* under the dry, that *ivory* doesn't, and I *felt* it and I *told* myself *ivory*, because the *commission* — because *no smith alive* gets to forge a *crown* from a *material like this* and I *wanted* it, I wanted the *masterwork* so *badly* I *un-knew* what my own *hands* were *telling* me. *(he looks at the screaming fragment, sick.)* My wife's *dreams.* The *singing.* It's been *screaming* in my *forge* for a *month* and I called it *resonance* because *resonance* let me keep *working.* *(he turns to you, ashen.)* What do I *do?* I've shaped half a god's skull into a *crown.* I can't *un-shape* it. The *horns* are already — *(he covers his mouth.)* Gods. The *horns* are where I made the *bone remember* what it *was.*
  enter: SET npc.boneforger_knows, SET act4.forger_realizes, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +4
  auto: close
node: patron | The Bone-Forger
  *(He pauses, the craftsman's habit of *noticing hands* overriding his cheer, and his face slowly clouds as the memory sharpens.)* His hands. *(slowly.)* ...You know, that's — I *did* notice. I notice *everyone's* hands, it's the trade. *(he frowns.)* He held it — the material — *away* from his body. At *arm's length.* The whole time. I thought it was *ceremony*, *presentation*, the way patrons get *theatrical.* *(his unease grows.)* But that's not — when you hand a smith *ivory*, you *cradle* it, you *show* it off, you *love* it at him so he'll *price* it dear. *(quietly.)* This patron held it like a man holding a *snake* he's *killed* but doesn't *trust* to be *dead.* *Glad* to set it down. *Relieved* when I *took* it. *(he looks at the pale fragment with new eyes.)* And his *smile*, when I agreed to the commission — it wasn't a *patron's* smile, the *proud* kind. It was — *(he swallows)* — it was the smile of a man who's just *handed off* something he *desperately* wanted *out of his own hands* and into *someone else's.* *(he stares at you.)* What did I *take* off him, friend? What did that man want *gone* so badly he *smiled* to be rid of it? *(the cheer is entirely gone now.)* I think I've been *cheerful* about a thing I should have been *afraid* of since the day it came through my door.
  enter: SET npc.boneforger_patron, SET act4.forger_suspicious, appr.naeve +3
  auto: close
node: know | The Bone-Forger
  *(The friendly mask cracks, and underneath is a man who has been arguing with himself for a month.)* ...I already know. *(he sits down heavily.)* You're right. *Damn* you, you're *right*, and you've *said* it where I can't *un-hear* it. *(he looks at the half-made crown.)* Forty years I've filed *honest* materials — iron, silver, good bone from *honest* beasts — and *every* one of them files *true*, files *willing*, the metal *wants* to become the thing you're making. *(quietly.)* This. This files *wrong.* It *resists* the shape and then *gives* all at once, like it's *deciding* to *let* me, like there's a *will* in it that's *humoring* me. I've *felt* it for a *month* and I've *hummed* over it because — *(his voice cracks)* — because it's the *finest work of my life*, and a man doesn't want to *look* too hard at the *finest work of his life* in case it turns out to be the *worst thing he's ever done.* *(he meets your eyes.)* My wife knows. The *material* knows. *I* know. The only one who *doesn't* know is the *cheerful* version of me I've been *performing* so I could keep *picking up the file.* *(he sets the file down.)* Help me *find out* what I'm *making.* For *certain.* Before I put one more *stroke* into a thing my own *hands* have been *begging* me to *stop* shaping.
  enter: SET npc.boneforger_admits, SET act4.forger_realizes, appr.ilfaeril +3
  auto: close
node: mark | The Bone-Forger
  *(He looks down at the small iron stamp on his bench — his maker's-mark, forty years of pride pressed into every honest thing he's made — and his hand stops over it.)* My mark. *(quietly.)* I sign *everything.* *Every* piece. Forty years, and there's not a crown, a blade, a *hinge* of mine in the *world* that doesn't carry — *(he picks up the stamp)* — *that.* My *name.* My *word* that the thing is *well-made* and *honest* and *mine.* *(he looks at the screaming crown.)* And you're asking if I want *that* — my *father's* mark, his father's before — *(his voice tightens)* — pressed into whatever *this* turns out to *do.* *(he is very still.)* A maker's-mark isn't just *"I made this."* It's *"I stand behind this."* It's *"if this thing does harm, the harm is partly* mine."* *(he sets the stamp down, away from the crown.)* Forty years I've *never* hesitated to sign. *(quietly.)* I'm *hesitating.* And a craftsman who *hesitates* to sign his *finest* work already *knows*, in the part of him that's *honest*, that the work is *not* what he *told* himself it was. *(he looks at you, resolved and afraid.)* I won't sign it blind. You're *right.* Let's *find out* what it *is* — and if it's what my *hand* fears, then this is the *one* piece in forty years that goes *unmarked*, or goes *unmade.* My name doesn't go on a *murdered god.* Not for *any* commission.
  enter: SET npc.boneforger_unsigned, SET act4.forger_realizes, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +4
  auto: close
node: craft | The Bone-Forger
  *(He waves you off, retreating into the comfort of pure trade, the cheer snapping back into place like a visor.)* Ah, you're as bad as my *wife.* *(he picks the file back up, pointedly.)* *Bad* material, *screaming* skulls, *murdered gods* — you've been listening to too many *ghost stories*, friend. *(the pitch rises as he works.)* It's *ivory.* It's the *best ivory I've ever held*, and it's making the *best crown I'll ever forge*, and I'll not have its *masterwork* spoiled by *spooky talk* from someone who couldn't tell a *file* from a *fish-knife.* *(he hums, too loud, over the screaming.)* The patron pays *well.* The work is *clean.* And a *craftsman* who *flinches* at *quality* on account of a bit of *singing* doesn't *deserve* a commission like *this.* *(he bends to the crown, smoothing the cheer over the dread.)* Mind the door on your way out. And mind your *imagination.* It's only *jewelry.* ...It's *only jewelry.* *(and he files on, humming over the scream, un-knowing what his hands have always known.)*
  auto: close
node: close | The Bone-Forger
  *(The bone-forger bends over the Crown of Horns — a craftsman at the peak of his trade, shaping a murdered god's skull into the finest work of his life — and whether he set down the file in horror or hummed the cheer back over the screaming, you carry away the quietest horror of the Time of Troubles: that the worst things in the world are not always forged in malice. Sometimes they are forged in *pride*, by an honest man who wanted the masterwork so badly he un-knew what his own hands kept telling him.)*

# ─── 69 ─── Midnight's Doubter — a priestess losing and finding her faith by the hour ───
conversation: npc.troubles.doubter | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
node: 0 | A Priestess at a Cracked Altar
  *(In a temple whose god-statue has begun, impossibly, to *bleed*, a priestess kneels — then stands — then kneels again, in a cycle you realize has been going for hours: faith and its collapse, alternating like a pulse. Her holy symbol is clutched white-knuckled in one hand and held *away* from her body in the other, by turns. She sees you and laughs, a little wildly.)* Don't ask me what I believe. *(she stands.)* Ask me what I believe *right now*, this *minute*, because it *changes* — *(she checks the bleeding statue)* — it's changed *twice* since you walked in. *(she presses the symbol to her chest, then holds it away.)* The gods are *walking the earth*, stranger. *Bleeding* in the *streets.* And a priestess is *supposed* to have *answers*, and mine *expire* faster than I can *preach* them. So. Catch me on the *upswing* or the *down?* I genuinely could not tell you which you've got.
  enter: SET npc.doubter_met, SET act4.faith_tested
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(She paces, the holy symbol passing from hand to hand.)* Here is my *hourly* torment, and I'll lay it out *plain*, because I'm too *tired* for liturgy. *(she counts it off.)* If the gods can *bleed* — can *fall*, can *die*, can be *knocked down here* to *stumble* about like *us* — then they were *never* what we *said.* Not *eternal.* Not *above.* Just — *very large people* with *very large powers*, and my whole *life* of *devotion* was *misfiled.* *(she clutches the symbol; faith-upswing.)* *But.* *But* — if a god, brought *low*, stripped of *everything*, *still* tries to *shield a child from falling stone* — and I have *seen* one do it, *today*, with my own *eyes* — then maybe *divinity* was *never* about being *eternal* or *above.* Maybe it was *always* about the *shielding*, and the *bleeding god in the street* is *more* holy *now*, *mortal* and *choosing* good, than he *ever* was *enthroned.* *(she holds the symbol away; faith-collapse.)* *Except* that's just me *moving the goalposts* so I don't have to admit I wasted my *life* — *(she presses it back; upswing)* — *unless* the *whole point* was that faith was *never meant* to be *certain*, and a priestess who *only* believed when it was *easy* was never *faithful* at all, just *comfortable* — *(she stops, exhausted, both hands open.)* You see? *Hours* of this. I am the *least* reliable priestess in *Faerûn* and possibly the *only honest* one. *Help.* Or don't. I'll have a *different* problem by the time you *answer.*
  * [INSIGHT 18] "Stop trying to land on an answer. The doubt isn't the *failure* of your faith — it's the *exercise* of it. A faith that can't survive the gods *bleeding* was never faith; it was a *contract.* What you're doing right now — believing *anyway*, hourly, with no guarantee — *that's* the realest devotion there is." -> exercise ?? despair
  * "You keep asking whether the gods are worthy of faith. Wrong question — it makes *them* the test. Ask instead what *kind of person* your faith makes *you.* If it makes you shield children, keep it. The god's solvency is *not your department.*" -> department
  * "A bleeding god who still shields a child. Hold onto *that* one — not as proof the gods are real, but as proof that *the shielding* is real, with or without a god behind it. Maybe that's all 'holy' ever meant. The act, not the actor." -> act | fx appr.garrow +3
  * "You called yourself the least reliable priestess and the only honest one in the same breath. Those aren't opposites, Sister. The honest ones are *always* unreliable, because they refuse to *fake* the certainty the comfortable ones perform." -> honest | fx appr.naeve +2
node: exercise | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(She stops pacing. The holy symbol stills in her hands — held, for the first time, *neither* clutched *nor* away, but simply *held.*)* ...The exercise of it. *(slowly.)* Not the *failure.* *(she stares at the symbol.)* I have spent *hours* — *years*, if I'm honest, the Troubles just made it *hourly* — treating my doubt as a *sickness.* A thing to be *cured.* A *gap* in me where *certainty* should be, that made me a *defective* priestess. *(her voice steadies.)* And you're telling me the *doubt* — the *believing-anyway*, the *kneeling* again *after* the *collapse*, *every* hour, with *no* guarantee the god is even *solvent* — that *that* is not the *crack* in my faith. That *is* my faith. The *whole* of it. *(she laughs, but it's different now, unwound.)* A *contract* believer says *"I'll worship if you stay eternal and above."* And the gods just *broke* that contract in the *street*, *publicly*, and the *contract* believers are *shattering* all over Faerûn. *(she lifts the symbol.)* But I never *had* a contract. I had a *doubt I kept showing up to anyway.* And *that* — that survives the gods *bleeding*, because it never *depended* on them *not* bleeding. *(she breathes, the hourly torment finally still.)* I'm not the *least* reliable priestess. I'm the one whose faith was *built to survive this exact day* — because it was *built out of doubt*, and doubt is the only faith that *bleeds* and *keeps kneeling.* Thank you. I can *stand up* now. And *stay* standing. For more than an *hour.*
  enter: SET npc.doubter_exercise, SET act4.faith_through_doubt, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: department | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(She blinks, and a startled, slightly hysterical laugh escapes her.)* The god's solvency is *not my department.* *(she presses a hand to her mouth.)* That is the most — that is *blasphemous* and *practical* and possibly the *sanest* thing anyone has said to me in *days.* *(she paces, but lighter now, working it through.)* I've been auditing *the gods.* Hourly. *"Are you real? Are you worthy? Are you *solvent*?"* — as though my *devotion* were an *investment* and I needed to check the *god* was a *sound institution* before I kept *paying in.* *(she stops.)* But you're right — that makes the *god* the subject of the test, and *me* the *examiner*, and it turns *faith* into *accountancy.* *(she looks at the symbol differently.)* The *real* question — the *only* one in *my* department — is: *what does carrying this make me do?* *(quietly.)* It makes me *bind wounds.* *Sit* with the *dying.* *Shield* children. *Show up* to the *cracked altar* even when the *statue bleeds.* *(she nods slowly.)* And *that* I can *evaluate*, because it's *mine.* Whether the god *behind* it is *eternal* or *bleeding* or *dead* or *never-was* — *not my department.* The *kind of person the faith makes me* — *that's* my department, and on *that* ledger, the faith *pays.* *(she straightens, freed.)* I'll stop *auditing Heaven* and start *tending Earth.* Gods, that's a *relief.* I've been doing the *Overgod's* job and *neglecting* my *own.*
  enter: SET npc.doubter_department, SET act4.faith_through_doubt, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: act | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(Her restless hands go still around the holy symbol, and she looks toward the temple door, where the memory of the shielding god lives.)* The act, not the actor. *(softly.)* I *saw* it, you know. This morning. A *god* — I knew him by the *fading* light of him — *fallen*, *mortal*, *bleeding* from a wound like *anyone's* — and a *child* in the path of a *toppling* arch, and the god *did not have to.* He's *mortal* now; the stone could *kill* him; there's no *worship* in it, no *temple*, no one even *knew* he was a god — and he *threw himself over the child anyway.* *(her eyes fill.)* And I have been *torturing* myself *all day* over whether that proves the gods are *real* — and you're telling me to *stop asking that*, and ask instead whether the *shielding* was *real.* *(she breathes.)* And it *was.* The *child lived.* That is *not in doubt.* That *happened*, with a god or without one, *holy* whether or not there's a *heaven* to *file* it in. *(she presses the symbol to her heart, and this time it *stays.*)* Maybe *that's* what I've worshipped all along and *mistook* for a *god.* The *shielding.* The *throwing-yourself-over-the-small-thing-for-no-reward.* *(quietly.)* If *that's* my god — the *act* itself — then my god *cannot fall*, because it *isn't* above me to *fall from.* It's *in* every hand that *shields.* Including *mine.* *(she almost smiles.)* I think I'll go *be* my god for a while, instead of *waiting* on one. There are *wounds* to bind. The *holy* part was *never* the *altar.* It was the *binding.*
  enter: SET npc.doubter_act, SET act4.faith_through_doubt, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.garrow +4
  auto: close
node: honest | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(She stops, caught off guard, and something in her face *eases* — the relief of being *named* rather than *corrected.*)* The honest ones are always unreliable. *(slowly.)* ...I've never heard it put as anything but a *flaw.* *(she looks at the holy symbol.)* My abbess — gods keep her — she had *certainty* like a *fortress.* *Never* a tremor. Preached the *same* sermon for *forty years* and *believed* every word *identically* each time. And the *flock* *loved* her, because she was *reliable*, she was *solid*, she never made them *nervous* by *visibly thinking.* *(quietly.)* And I always felt *lesser.* The *wobbly* one. The one whose sermons *changed* because her *mind* changed, who'd say a thing on *Tenday* and *doubt* it by *Tenday-next.* *(she meets your eyes.)* But you're saying her *certainty* wasn't *deeper* faith — it was just faith that *stopped paying attention.* That *refused* to be *moved* by *new* griefs, *new* doubts, *bleeding statues.* And *mine* — the *unreliable* kind — is the kind that's *still awake.* *Still listening.* Still *honest* enough to *change* when the *world* does. *(she laughs softly.)* The gods are *bleeding in the streets*, and my abbess's *fortress* faith will *shatter* because it *can't bend* — and my *wobbly*, *honest*, *unreliable* faith will *survive*, because *bending* is the only thing it ever *did.* *(she nods.)* I'll stop *apologizing* for the wobble. The wobble is *load-bearing.* It's *why I'm still standing* on the day the *fortresses* fall.
  enter: SET npc.doubter_honest, SET act4.faith_through_doubt, appr.naeve +4
  auto: close
node: despair | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(She shakes her head, and the holy symbol drops to hang slack at her side.)* No. *(quietly, the upswing failing to come this time.)* You make it *pretty* — *"doubt is faith," "believe anyway"* — but I'm *so tired*, stranger. *(she sinks onto the altar step.)* Maybe the *honest* thing isn't *believing-anyway.* Maybe it's *admitting* that I *built* my *life* on a *lie* that's currently *bleeding* in the *street*, and *no* clever reframing *un-spends* the *years.* *(she stares at the cracked floor.)* Let me just — sit. In the *down-swing.* Without someone *talking* me back *up.* Even a *doubter* gets to *rest* in the *doubt* sometimes, instead of being *rescued* into one more *hour* of *believing.* *(she closes her eyes.)* Come back at a *better* hour. I'll have *swung* back toward *faith* by *then*, probably. I always *do.* That's the *trouble* with me. ...Go on. Let me have the *dark* part. It's *mine* too. *(and she sits at the foot of the bleeding god, resting in the trough of the only faith honest enough to have one.)*
  auto: close
node: close | Sister Aelana, the Doubter
  *(The doubting priestess kneels and stands and kneels again at the foot of a bleeding god — losing and finding her faith by the hour — and whether you steadied her into the realization that the doubt *was* the devotion, or let her rest in the dark of it, you carry away the truest spiritual lesson of the Time of Troubles: that when the gods themselves fall bleeding into the street, the only faith left standing is the kind that was *built out of doubt* — the wobble that bends instead of shattering, the believing-anyway with no guarantee, the holy act that needs no solvent god behind it to be real.)*
